

#Abstract

JavaDesk is a voice-based smart desktop assistant developed using Java that focuses on task-based and mode-based automation to enhance user productivity. 
The system is designed to automate common desktop activities such as opening applications, folders, and websites, managing daily routines, and generating usage reports through predefined or user-created modes like "Study Mode" or "Work Mode". 
Unlike traditional macro tools that rely on low-level keyboard and mouse event recording, JavaDesk implements high-level automation to ensure system stability, security, and academic suitability.

The assistant provides both voice and graphical user interfaces, enabling users to interact through text or speech commands. 
Voice input is processed using speech-to-text technology, while text-to-speech is used to deliver confirmations and notifications.
A rule-based command processing module interprets user commands and executes corresponding actions. JavaDesk also supports guided macro creation through voice interaction and time-based triggers that automatically execute tasks at scheduled intervals using a background scheduler.

Additionally, the system tracks assistant-driven screen time and mode usage to generate daily productivity reports. 
All macros, triggers, and usage data are stored locally using lightweight file-based storage.
With its modular architecture, safe automation approach, and practical real-world relevance, JavaDesk serves as an effective and academically strong desktop automation solution developed entirely in Java.

